[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We welcome the arrival of the EU into space policy. Space is increasingly vital for delivering public policy at local, regional, national and supra-national levels, and has a key role in reaching Lisbon Treaty objectives of a smart, sustainable and inclusive economy by creating high-skilled jobs, commercial opportunities, boosting innovation and improving citizens’ well-being and security. For example, Copernicus (formerly GMES) is a vital tool for the EU in environmental protection.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Given ESA
[normal]’
[normal]s success, 
[normal]we
[normal] share the UK Government
[normal]’s concern about any 
[normal]overly hasty move to bring ESA under the wing of the EU, and 
[normal]support
[normal] the Government
[normal]’
[normal]s cautious approach to moving the two institutions closer together.
[normal] 
[normal]To align the need for coordination with the importance of maintaining distinct roles, t
[normal]he 
[normal]Commission’s proposal
[normal] for ESA to set up a specific ESA directorate in charge of implementing EU programmes, under EU rules, should be evaluated.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] 
[normal]We
[normal] 
[normal]strongly support an EU role as space p
[normal]olicy lead and sponsor for downstream services dedicated to socio-economic applications.
[normal] 
[normal]We
[normal] would like to see this EU role, promoting space exploitation, 
[normal]better
[normal] reflected 
[normal]and co-ordinated 
[normal]in Horizon 2020.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Overall UK advocacy in EU space areas remains under-resourced and under-structured, partly reflecting the fast evolving natur
[normal]e of the EU’s space landscape. W
[normal]e encourage UKSA to review and strengthen its own resourcing in
[normal] relation 
[normal]to EU space matters
[normal], including, for instance, 
[normal]promotion of
[normal] more UK nationals in the EU’s growing space policy community
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]R&amp;D is 
[normal]an important enabler 
[normal]of economic growth
[normal] and underpins the competitiveness of the space industry
[normal].  
[normal]The innovation component of the EU’s next seven-year budget is
[normal] an opportunity to 
[normal]build
[normal] a platform for growth 
[normal]and competitiveness
[normal]. Asia, for example, currently reinvests 3.5% of total GDP in R&amp;
[normal]D
[normal], whilst Europe commits just 2%. Placing Horizo
[normal]n 2020
[normal] at the centre of Europe's 
[normal]economic plans 
[normal]would send a very clear message that the EU and its 
[normal]M
[normal]ember 
[normal]S
[normal]tates are committed to fostering innovation and 
[normal]economic 
[normal]growth
[normal];
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The long-term nature of R&amp;D cycles in the space sector means that stable funding is especially important for businesses. EU funding should focus on the very early stages of technology development in order to mitigate the risks for companies, universities and individuals investing in experimental technology and in 
[normal]proving the feasibility of new
[normal] satellite-enabled service capabilities
[normal];
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A specific weakness of the EC’s FP7 research programme has been lack of funding for satellite communications and satellite navigation applications.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] DG ENT
[normal]R
[normal]’s space research programme largely ignores telecommunications, despite the contribution of satellite communications to growth and public policy, 
[normal]e.g.
[normal] in the EU Digital Agenda targets for 2020 for deployment of high-speed broadband to all European citizens. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Funding for developing satellite navigation applications has also been lacking in recent years, despite the progress made on the launch of the 
[normal]Galileo
[normal] satellites
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is essential that these 
[normal]omissions 
[normal]are 
[normal]corrected
[normal] in Horizon 2020
[normal].
