[normal]4.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]UKSA has been significantly under-resourced, affecting its relationships with industry, and degrading the perceived transparency of its decision-making.  Examples are in dealing with EC communications and in producing the
[normal] promised National Space Policy;
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We
[normal] believe that there are a number of improvements that could be made by UKSA
[normal].
[normal] These
[normal] include the need for UKSA to
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The failure of the UK to achieve any director in ESA, compared with three each for France, Italy and Germany, is a failure of
[normal] ambition and influence by UKSA;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]On the European front to maintain momentum with ESA 
[normal]the UKSA
[normal] must influence their Programmes to meet UK policy objectives. 
[normal]They
[normal] must 
[normal]try to 
[normal]optimise the return from our
[normal] ESA subscriptions in terms of noble w
[normal]ork which is focused on technologies with real market potential wherever possible
[normal];
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]UKSA must work closely with industry to ensure that together 
[normal]we
[normal] are delivering on growth. The current work on the IGS is vital to reach the target 10% share of the global market by 2030.   Growth is driven by the downstream services market so we must target key sectors for growth and work with the other Catapults to fully exploit these markets. 
[normal]Working in partnership with other government departments the UKSA can work pro-actively to unlock barriers to market, support access to export markets and thus take science and technology into the global marketplace
[normal];
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Effective ESA 
[normal]and EC 
[normal]engagement requires complementary national funding to create the conditions in which industry can win greater share
[normal]s
[normal] of ESA noble work
[normal] and EU funding
[normal]. This approach is well recognised and practised by our 
[normal]inter
[normal]national competitors. 
[normal]We
[normal] therefore welcome the establishment of the National Space Technology Programme (a key recommendation of the first Space IGS in 2010) and its refinancing in the Autumn Statement of 2012. However, a stronger NSTP 
[normal]is 
[normal]an essential test of UKSA’s commitment to help maximise UK economic return from EU and ESA space spend
[normal]. This is also key to
[normal] risk reduction of new commercial initiatives which can then attract City funding.
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The UK has 
[normal]developed world leadership in both space science and in commercial export markets, part
[normal]ly from 
[normal]targeted investment in ESA programmes with proven 
[normal]scientific and 
[normal]economic 
[normal]potential, notably ARTES.  However, 
[normal]a better balance between national and ESA investment is essential if the UK is to fully explo
[normal]it its ESA (and EU) investments;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] 
[normal]ESA is a vital wealth creation mechanism for the UK space-enabled economy, providing an excellent means for UK
[normal]-
[normal]based operators to leverage off leading edge UK technologies
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]enabling 
[normal]UK exports of high value 
[normal]satellite systems and services
[normal];
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Early decisions on investment in ESA programmes helps create a more strategic and long-term UK agenda in ESA; it helps industry plan ahead, develop technology roadmaps and identify export opportunities. It is vital that the UK invest strongly in the early phases of major programmes, in order to get sufficient control to deliver UK technology priorities an
[normal]d maximise growth opportunities;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] 
[normal]Industry
[normal] has demonstrated that there are strong
[normal] commercial spinoff benefits from 
[normal]earth observation, 
[normal]space science
[normal] 
[normal]and robotic exploration 
[normal]in terms of
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]technologies
[normal],
[normal] and also in terms of software and services to the global Space market
[normal];
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The UK has demonstrated that it achieves a better return on investment than other ESA Member States. This is primarily through its highly developed capacity to take ESA developed technology to the commercial market. It is also strongly influenced by the UK selection of ESA optional programmes that are better aligned to the global marketplace. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]6.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There 
[normal]should be a
[normal] clear UK owner or overseer of resilience plans for the satellites and ground-based supporting infrastructures that provide critical UK 
[normal]capabilities
[normal] and
[normal] 
[normal]a
[normal] comprehensive analysis of space systems critical to the UK
[normal]. This should 
[normal]include 
[normal]an analysis of
[normal] the level of resilience of space-related capabilities or of mitigation measures in the event of disruption
[normal];
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The threats from natural events in space are well understood
[normal] and ESA has an on-going programme to provide monitoring and 
[normal]warnings of Space Weather events
[normal];
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] Due to the sensitivities associated with Space Debris and the associated tracking of objects in earth orbit, the UKSA should look to other European nations such as Germany and France to develop ground based national systems to protect critical national space assets outside of ESA programmes.
